  Journals foundation:

  1. User speaks/writes into a Journal (the input)
  2. DSL parses activity lines (the structure)
  3. Tasks emerge (the actionable output)
  4. Neo4j tracks relationships (the intelligence layer)

  This is SKUEL as a To Do list manager that learns — rooted in the act of journaling.

  Why This Is Powerful

  The DSL being designed (@context(task), @when(), @priority(), @ku(), @link()) transforms freeform journaling into structured action.

  The user doesn't feel like they're "using a productivity app" — they're just reflecting,
  talking, writing.

  Yet underneath, SKUEL is:

  - Extracting tasks
  - Linking them to goals
  - Connecting knowledge being applied
  - Tracking energy patterns
  - Building a life graph

  The simplicity of "To Do list" is the entry point.

  The graph is the depth.

  Current Codebase Alignment

  Looking at what exists:
  - Assignments/Journals architecture is ready (ProcessingPipelineService)
  - Tasks service with full CRUD
  - Graph relationships between tasks, goals, knowledge
  - UserContext aggregating everything

  What's missing is the DSL parser — the bridge from Journal text to structured entities.

