 Created a working DSL parser for SKUEL that implements your v0.3 Activity Syntax spec. Here's what was built:

  Files Created

  | File                                           | Purpose                    | Lines |
  |------------------------------------------------|----------------------------|-------|
  | core/services/dsl/__init__.py                  | Module exports             | 40    |
  | core/services/dsl/activity_dsl_parser.py       | Core parser                | ~450  |
  | core/services/dsl/activity_entity_converter.py | Converts to SKUEL entities | ~300  |
  | tests/test_dsl_parser.py                       | 31 passing tests           | ~350  |

  Architecture

  Journal Text
      ↓
  ActivityDSLParser.parse_journal()
      ↓
  ParsedJournal (list of ParsedActivityLine)
      ↓
  ActivityEntityConverter.convert_journal()
      ↓
  {
    "tasks": [TaskCreateRequest, ...],
    "habits": [dict, ...],
    "goals": [dict, ...],
    "events": [dict, ...]
  }
      ↓
  Existing SKUEL Services (TasksCoreService.create_task(), etc.)
      ↓
  Neo4j Graph

  DSL Syntax Supported

  - [ ] Description @context(task) @when(2025-11-27T09:30) @priority(1)
        @duration(90m) @energy(focus) @ku(ku:sel/mindfulness) @link(goal:health)

  | Tag         | Purpose                | Example                                  |
  |-------------|------------------------|------------------------------------------|
  | @context()  | Entity type (required) | @context(task), @context(habit,learning) |
  | @when()     | Scheduled time         | @when(2025-11-27T09:30)                  |
  | @priority() | Importance 1-5         | @priority(1)                             |
  | @duration() | Time estimate          | @duration(90m), @duration(1h30m)         |
  | @repeat()   | Habit recurrence       | @repeat(daily), @repeat(weekly:Mon,Wed)  |
  | @energy()   | Energy states          | @energy(focus,creative)                  |
  | @ku()       | Knowledge unit         | @ku(ku:sel/mindfulness)                  |
  | @link()     | Graph connections      | @link(goal:health, principle:balance)    |

  Usage Example

  from core.services.dsl import parse_journal_text

  journal_text = """
  ### Today's Focus

  - [ ] Morning meditation @context(habit) @duration(20m) @energy(spiritual)
  - [ ] Write proposal @context(task) @priority(1) @when(2025-11-27T09:00)
  - [ ] Learn Python async @context(learning) @ku(ku:tech/python-async)
  """

  result = parse_journal_text(journal_text)
  if result.is_ok:
      parsed = result.value
      print(f"Found {len(parsed.get_tasks())} tasks")
      print(f"Found {len(parsed.get_habits())} habits")


      The foundation is now in place. The DSL parser transforms the simple act of journaling into structured action — exactly the SKUEL philosophy of "actions over theory."


